<div id="review_3728554875" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3728554875" />
    <a title="Amanda" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5793497-amanda"><img alt="Amanda" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1453990378p2/5793497.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3728554875?book_show_action=true">Feb 17, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amanda" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amanda" href="/user/show/5793497-amanda">Amanda</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audible Audio " href="/book/show/45164087-8-mindful-steps-to-happiness">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5793497-amanda?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5793497-amanda?shelf=buddhism">buddhism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3728554875" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15791752995194392551">Perhaps I feel rather neutral on this because I listened to it as an audiobook. Perhaps I would have felt more like more meaningful learning came through if I read it physically. Regardless, I felt the beginning of the book was strong, and I enjoyed the early steps laid out (skillful understanding, thinking, speech, livelihood, effort) but the later steps felt very proscriptive about meditation. I acknowledge that absolutely the author has greater experience than I do but I also found the proscr</span>
  <span id="freeText15791752995194392551" style="display:none">Perhaps I feel rather neutral on this because I listened to it as an audiobook. Perhaps I would have felt more like more meaningful learning came through if I read it physically. Regardless, I felt the beginning of the book was strong, and I enjoyed the early steps laid out (skillful understanding, thinking, speech, livelihood, effort) but the later steps felt very proscriptive about meditation. I acknowledge that absolutely the author has greater experience than I do but I also found the proscriptive information regarding meditation to be in direct contrast to earlier information delivered in the book about how we shouldn't become too tied to ceremony. <br /><br />I was particularly bothered by one portion where he describes knowing that a meditator at a retreat had dozed off because they were "rhythmically" swaying forward and backward. Then the author said that the meditator came out of the session and said how great it was but he knew that they had fallen asleep. This bothered me as both it made an assumption about whether or not the meditator was telling the truth when they said afterward that was a positive session. But also it bothered me as swaying is often a stim for neurodiverse people - just because someone is stimming doesn't mean they aren't meditating. I'm reminded of a story a monk told once in a Dharma session about the Buddha advising someone who said to the Buddha that they couldn't meditate without repetitively rubbing a piece of cloth and how to stop, and the Buddha told them not to worry about stopping if it helped them meditate. This story seems to stand in direct contrast to the one told by the author, and the Buddha's was more inclusive.<br /><br />So I enjoyed the beginning of the book but the last half to third of it felt non-inclusive overly proscriptive to me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15791752995194392551" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

